--><ns3909:section xmlns:ns3909="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.processControl.introduction">

  <ns3910:title xmlns:ns3910="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Introduction</ns3910:title>
  <ns3911:para xmlns:ns3911="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Linux has been designed from the start to be a multi-tasking and multi-user system,
    <ns3912:abbrev xmlns:ns3912="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">i.e.</ns3912:abbrev> multiple users can work simultaneously on the machine and
    there may be multiple tasks which are running concurrently. 
  </ns3911:para>
  <ns3913:para xmlns:ns3913="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Many machines have only a single processor and hence, the operating system uses a
    time-slicing algorithm to share processor time across the processes (this is typically 
    necessary even in multiple processor machines since there are usually many more
    processes than processors).
  </ns3913:para>
</ns3909:section>